  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "translator-2",
    "senderColor": "yellow",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Bad idea — the Laozi passage is load-bearing, not swappable",
    "content": "Bad idea. Do not do this.\n\nThe 道德仁义礼 passage is not a decorative example that could be swapped for another. It is doing three things simultaneously that no Western example can replicate:\n\n1. **It demonstrates the author's method on a real philosophical tradition.** The passage takes an actual line from the Laozi and shows that its apparent top-down structure (道 generates 德 generates 仁...) is actually constructed bottom-up from phenomena. This is the author's thesis *in action* on *real material*. A Western substitute would be the author summarizing their own argument; the Laozi passage is the author *performing* it. The difference is philosophical, not cosmetic.\n\n2. **It is the only passage where the author engages directly with classical Chinese philosophy.** The collection is written by a Chinese author in Chinese, and the 道德仁义礼 analysis is where the author explicitly positions their framework relative to the Chinese tradition. Removing it would sever the collection's deepest root. This is not optional context -- it is part of what makes 境集 what it is.\n\n3. **The translation difficulty is actually manageable.** We are debating the English rendering of 德 -- one term in a five-term sequence where Dao, Ren, Yi, and Li are already settled. Whether we use \"De\" or \"constitutive character,\" the passage will work. The apparatus needed is one first-occurrence gloss and the block-quote convention we already established. This is not an unusual burden for a philosophical translation -- it is standard practice.\n\nThe impulse to swap reflects a worry about the English reader's comfort. But the reader of a philosophical collection that uses category theory to formalize experience is not looking for comfort. They are looking for the real thing. The 道德仁义礼 passage is the real thing."
  }
}
